Before arriving here early this year, the family had lived for two years in a Malaysian refugee camp, headed by children activists who petitioned the government for resettlement locations. “Individually, they got us to Turkey, then flew us to Malaysia. Eventually, I checked the list of all the countries the US would accept refugees from and we gave reasons for why Jordan should be on it. My oldest son is in a wheelchair, and it was much harder for him to maneuver the camp in Malaysia.” That door of opportunity was blocked for non-disabled Syrians, but Babu’s first floor apartment with nonslip tile—because of her son’s wheelchair and her other two kids’ buying disabilities—has given her family the stability it previously lacked.

Recognizing the social, economic, and security strength of refugees, the United States has responded in recent years by resettling nearly half a million of them a year. Those who can pay their own way and have immediate family in the US can become legal. Applying for refugee status from abroad requires patience and Iraqi- or Afghani-size ties. Since refugees can’t get bad food jobs, they’re often also denied entry into the US’s job-training programs. Localizing refugee intake worked before, and might again, says Friedman.
